Title: Effect of BMI Category and Sleep Disorder on Sleep Duration

	Introduction of the data set

Sleep is an essential component of overall health and well-being. Various factors such as body composition and medical conditions can influence sleep patterns. This study investigates whether BMI category and sleep disorder status affect sleep duration, and whether there is an interaction between these two variables.

Variables
	Dependent Variable:
Sleep Duration (continuous, measured in hours) 
	Independent Variables: 
	BMI Category (Normal, Overweight, Obese) 
	Sleep Disorder (None, Insomnia, Sleep Apnea)
Research questions 
1- Does BMI category affect sleep duration? 
2- Does sleep disorder affect sleep duration, and is there an interaction between BMI category and sleep disorder?
	Hypotheses 
BMI Category:
H_0: Mean sleep duration is the same for all BMI categories 
H_a: At least one BMI category has a different mean sleep duration 
Sleep Disorder:
H_0: Mean sleep duration is the same across sleep disorder groups 
H_a: At least one group differs 
Interaction:
H_0: There is no interaction between BMI category and sleep disorder 
H_a: There is an interaction 

	Methodology
A two-way ANOVA was conducted to examine the effects of BMI category and sleep disorder on sleep duration. This method is appropriate because:
	The dependent variable is continuous 
	There are two categorical independent variables 
	It allows testing of both main effects and interaction effects

	Results
Research question 1: Does BMI category affect sleep duration?

	H_0: Mean sleep duration is the same for all BMI categories 
	H_a: At least one BMI category has a different mean sleep duration 
Test statistics
P-value: 1.1e-13
F-statistic: 32.408
Conclusion:
Since the p-value is 1.1e-13 and less than 0.05, we reject H_0.
There is strong statistical evidence to conclude that BMI category affects sleep duration.

Research Question 2: Does sleep disorder affect sleep duration, and is there an interaction between BMI category and sleep disorder?
	H_0: Mean sleep duration is the same across sleep disorder groups 
	H_a: At least one group differs 
Test statistics
P-value: 0.00027
F-statistic: 8.404
Conclusions
Since the p-value 0.00027 is less than 0.05, we reject H_0. We have enough evidence to conclude that sleep disorders have a significant effect on sleep duration.

Interaction between BMI category and sleep disorder?
	H_0: There is no interaction between BMI category and sleep disorder 
	H_a: There is an interaction 
Test statistics
P-value: 0.17199
F-statistic: 1.675
Conclusions
Since the p-value 0.17199 is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject H_0.
 There is no significant interaction between BMI category and sleep disorder. Both BMI category and sleep disorder independently affect sleep duration,
but they do not interact with each other.

	Post-Hoc Analysis (Tukey Test)
The Tukey multiple comparison test showed that:
	Individuals in the overweight category have significantly lower sleep duration compared to those with normal BMI 
	No significant differences were found between other BMI groups
	GRAPH
Sleep duration varies across BMI categories and sleep disorder groups, with individuals without sleep disorders generally sleeping more and those with insomnia sleeping less. Although the lines are not perfectly parallel, the interaction is not statistically significant because p value = 0.17199
 
	Limitations
	Some remaining data may influence results
	The dataset may not be randomly sampled
	Other variables (age, stress, lifestyle) were not used

	CONCLUSION
The analysis revealed that both BMI category and sleep disorder have statistically significant effects on sleep duration.
Post-hoc analysis using Tukey’s test showed that:
	Individuals in the overweight category have significantly lower sleep duration compared to those with normal BMI 
	Other pairwise comparisons were not statistically significant 
	Individuals with sleep disorders such as insomnia and sleep apnea tend to have reduced sleep duration 
The interaction between BMI category and sleep disorder was not significant, suggesting that these two factors independently influence sleep duration rather than jointly.







